1
00:00:00,789 --> 00:00:04,460
What time frame to use when day trading is
an important choice.

2
00:00:04,460 --> 00:00:08,990
And the right time frame will vary by each
person, the strategy they use, and how they

3
00:00:08,990 --> 00:00:13,660
like to spend their trading time (meaning
a more relaxed trading session versus more

4
00:00:13,660 --> 00:00:15,019
intense one).

5
00:00:15,019 --> 00:00:18,840
In this video we’ll talk about a simple
concept to choose the right time frame for

6
00:00:18,840 --> 00:00:24,110
day trading, in order to make the right decision
right from the beginning.

7
00:00:24,110 --> 00:00:27,750
Professional traders spend little time choosing
a time frame.

8
00:00:27,750 --> 00:00:31,650
Their choice of time frame isn't based on
their trading strategy or the market in which

9
00:00:31,650 --> 00:00:32,820
they're trading.

10
00:00:32,820 --> 00:00:35,770
It's based on their own trading personality.

11
00:00:35,770 --> 00:00:42,260
Before we begin, here is a chart that shows
the difference between a 1, 5, and 15-minute

12
00:00:42,260 --> 00:00:43,260
chart.

13
00:00:43,260 --> 00:00:48,420
They all show 12 hours of price data on the
same day, but, as you notice, there is a significant

14
00:00:48,420 --> 00:00:50,250
difference in detail.

15
00:00:50,250 --> 00:00:54,739
So let’s talk about the benefits and drawbacks
of each day trading time frame so you can

16
00:00:54,739 --> 00:00:58,930
decide which one is right for you.

17
00:00:58,930 --> 00:01:05,890
A 1-minute time frame may work well for someone
who likes seeing detail in the price movements

18
00:01:05,890 --> 00:01:11,290
and potentially getting in and out for short-term
trades that only last a few minutes.

19
00:01:11,290 --> 00:01:16,150
Trading the one-minute requires nearly constant
attention while trading, since candles are

20
00:01:16,150 --> 00:01:20,960
generated every minute and trade signals can
occur often (depending on your strategy, of

21
00:01:20,960 --> 00:01:22,600
course).

22
00:01:22,600 --> 00:01:27,620
Because price bars occur frequently, 1-minute
chart traders typically have the opportunity

23
00:01:27,620 --> 00:01:31,409
to take more trades per day compared to other
time frames.

24
00:01:31,409 --> 00:01:37,060
With a winning system, more trades means more
profit and faster compounding of the account.

25
00:01:37,060 --> 00:01:41,860
But with the potential for more activity,
a trader who doesn’t have a good risk management

26
00:01:41,860 --> 00:01:45,510
strategy can diminish their capital rapidly.

27
00:01:45,510 --> 00:01:49,850
On a 1-min time frame, it’s possible to
make several trades within a two-hour trading

28
00:01:49,850 --> 00:01:50,950
session.

29
00:01:50,950 --> 00:01:54,830
And it’s perfect if you don’t want to
spend too many hours in front of your screen.

30
00:01:54,830 --> 00:01:59,759
With trades based on smaller candles, stop
losses and profit targets tend to be smaller

31
00:01:59,759 --> 00:02:02,630
than those used by higher time frame traders.

32
00:02:02,630 --> 00:02:04,200
This doesn’t have to be the case, though.

33
00:02:04,200 --> 00:02:08,860
A trader could use a small stop loss on the
1-minute chart and aim for large reward:risk

34
00:02:08,860 --> 00:02:09,860
trade.

35
00:02:09,860 --> 00:02:13,959
The main takeaway is that the 1-minute time
frame is for people who want to maximize their

36
00:02:13,959 --> 00:02:19,439
trading time with more trades, typically with
slightly increased position sizes, using small

37
00:02:19,439 --> 00:02:25,230
stop losses and profit targets.

38
00:02:25,230 --> 00:02:29,989
A 5-minute chart may work well for someone
who focuses on bigger intraday trends and

39
00:02:29,989 --> 00:02:34,849
doesn’t need to see the open-high-low-close
price every minute, but would rather get data

40
00:02:34,849 --> 00:02:37,239
over 5-minute periods.

41
00:02:37,239 --> 00:02:41,389
Trading the five-minute requires focus, but
less constant attention than the 1-minute

42
00:02:41,389 --> 00:02:46,209
chart because candles are forming every five
minutes, so there is more time between data

43
00:02:46,209 --> 00:02:47,489
points.

44
00:02:47,489 --> 00:02:51,849
If you wait for the candle to close before
acting, this means no action is taken for

45
00:02:51,849 --> 00:02:54,530
at least 5 minute intervals, and often longer.

46
00:02:54,530 --> 00:02:56,019
Thus, 5-minute chart traders tend to trade
less than 1-minute chart traders because there

47
00:02:56,019 --> 00:02:57,019
are fewer candles to act on.

48
00:02:57,019 --> 00:03:01,209
Depending on your strategy, one or two trades
may develop in a two-hour trading session,

49
00:03:01,209 --> 00:03:04,310
possibly more, but less than on the 1-minute
time frame.

50
00:03:04,310 --> 00:03:08,069
Stop losses and profit targets tend to be
a larger than on the 1-minute chart.

51
00:03:08,069 --> 00:03:12,599
This isn’t good or bad, but it does typically
mean fewer trades per day.

52
00:03:12,599 --> 00:03:16,769
Because candles and price swings are bigger
on the 5-minute chart, this means a greater

53
00:03:16,769 --> 00:03:20,219
distance between the chosen entry and exit.

54
00:03:20,219 --> 00:03:24,599
So the main takeaway is that the 5-minute
chart is for people who want to focus on larger

55
00:03:24,599 --> 00:03:29,709
intra-day movements, recieving fewer signals,
with moderate positions sizes.

56
00:03:29,709 --> 00:03:37,260
A 15-minute time frame is for someone who
wants to see the major trends and movements

57
00:03:37,260 --> 00:03:39,120
throughout the trading day.

58
00:03:39,120 --> 00:03:44,139
Trading on 15 minute chart requires less constant
focus because candles are occurring over a

59
00:03:44,139 --> 00:03:45,689
longer period.

60
00:03:45,689 --> 00:03:50,420
If you wait for candles to close then there
is at least 15 minute period between possible

61
00:03:50,420 --> 00:03:51,749
actions.

62
00:03:51,749 --> 00:03:55,329
Traders on this time frame may only be taking
one or two trades per day.

63
00:03:55,329 --> 00:04:00,419
But if you are only trading during a two-hour
session, many days may have no trade signals.

64
00:04:00,419 --> 00:04:04,900
So trading this time frame may require more
time in front of the screen since it takes

65
00:04:04,900 --> 00:04:09,159
longer to get into and out of trades.

66
00:04:09,159 --> 00:04:13,681
Stop losses and profit targets tend to be
larger than on the 5-minute chart, so this

67
00:04:13,681 --> 00:04:15,969
means fewer trades per day.

68
00:04:15,969 --> 00:04:20,600
Positions sizes are usually smaller than those
on a 5-minute chart because candles and price

69
00:04:20,600 --> 00:04:24,630
swings are bigger, which likely means a greater
stop loss distance.

70
00:04:24,630 --> 00:04:29,190
But because of fewer trades and a smaller
position size, it is easier to have multiple

71
00:04:29,190 --> 00:04:30,190
positions.

72
00:04:30,190 --> 00:04:34,600
The main takeaway is that the 15-minute chart
is for people who want to focus on the large

73
00:04:34,600 --> 00:04:36,380
price movements throughout the day.

74
00:04:36,380 --> 00:04:42,190
If you don’t mind waiting longer for trades
to open and close, if you prefer cleaner movement

75
00:04:42,190 --> 00:04:46,621
and if you plan only one or two trades over
multiple hours of trading, then the 15-min

76
00:04:46,621 --> 00:04:49,470
time frame might work for you.

77
00:04:49,470 --> 00:04:54,250
Some traders only day trade on one time frame,
while others trade multiple time frames to

78
00:04:54,250 --> 00:04:56,280
produce trading opportunities.

79
00:04:56,280 --> 00:05:00,900
A single time frame means you see a trade
on the 1-minute chart (or whatever time frame

80
00:05:00,900 --> 00:05:02,680
you use) and you take that trade.

81
00:05:02,680 --> 00:05:07,370
Multiple time frame trading means you look
at a longer-term chart and use it as a filter

82
00:05:07,370 --> 00:05:09,530
for trades on the lower time frame.

83
00:05:09,530 --> 00:05:14,590
In this case, a trader may check the 15-minute
for the overall trend direction, and then

84
00:05:14,590 --> 00:05:20,580
look for opportunities to enter in that trend
direction on the 1-minute chart, for example.

85
00:05:20,580 --> 00:05:24,560
Most day traders pick one time-frame and then
almost never leave it.

86
00:05:24,560 --> 00:05:28,490
They are so locked into their time frame that
they forget about the bigger picture.

87
00:05:28,490 --> 00:05:33,180
The other extreme are traders that constantly
jump from timeframe to timeframe without much

88
00:05:33,180 --> 00:05:34,180
of a plan.

89
00:05:34,180 --> 00:05:38,930
That’s why the best solution is a top-down
multiple time frame analysis where you start

90
00:05:38,930 --> 00:05:44,220
on the higher timeframe, the 15 min or 30
min time frame, look for the bigger picture

91
00:05:44,220 --> 00:05:49,300
perspective and then slowly build your trading
plan by going lower.

92
00:05:49,300 --> 00:05:53,340
And don’t start your analysis on the lowest
time-frame and then work your way up to the

93
00:05:53,340 --> 00:05:54,830
higher time-frames.

94
00:05:54,830 --> 00:05:59,550
This creates a very narrow and one-dimensional
view and it misses the point of the multiple

95
00:05:59,550 --> 00:06:01,290
time frame analysis.

96
00:06:01,290 --> 00:06:06,720
Now, time frames are often discussed as if
they are the only charting option.

97
00:06:06,720 --> 00:06:07,720
They are not.

98
00:06:07,720 --> 00:06:12,060
There are chart types based on things other
than time and one of them is the range bar

99
00:06:12,060 --> 00:06:13,060
chart.

100
00:06:13,060 --> 00:06:17,090
Range bars are bars that are plotted on a
chart that have the same price increment,

101
00:06:17,090 --> 00:06:21,660
the same height, and each bar closes either
at the high or the low, regardless of the

102
00:06:21,660 --> 00:06:23,180
opening price.

103
00:06:23,180 --> 00:06:28,090
There is no time component as you would see
with candlestick charts or bar charts.

104
00:06:28,090 --> 00:06:32,430
In Tradingview for example, if you want a
range of 10 pips on the Pound Dollar and you

105
00:06:32,430 --> 00:06:36,310
are trading with range bars, set your range
to 100.

106
00:06:36,310 --> 00:06:40,670
Every time the pair moves 10 pips up or down
in total for that bar, it will complete the

107
00:06:40,670 --> 00:06:42,900
current bar and start a new one.

108
00:06:42,900 --> 00:06:46,200
So time has no effect.

109
00:06:46,200 --> 00:06:50,220
Here are the key takeaways to keep in mind
when day trading with range bars:

110
00:06:50,220 --> 00:06:54,200
All range bars are uniform in size because
the range is constant

111
00:06:54,200 --> 00:07:00,060
You can choose any bar size you want, based
on your needs (you can select a 4 pip, a 39

112
00:07:00,060 --> 00:07:04,780
pip or any size you want)
The time period covered by each bar is irrelevant

113
00:07:04,780 --> 00:07:09,370
as range bars are time-independent
For this reason, range bars can help you to

114
00:07:09,370 --> 00:07:12,870
identify ranging price action in a blink of
an eye.

115
00:07:12,870 --> 00:07:18,090
And potential support and resistance levels
are more clearly visible on the chart.

116
00:07:18,090 --> 00:07:22,060
Probably the biggest advantage, especially
for day trading and scalping, is that lot

117
00:07:22,060 --> 00:07:26,450
of the false signals that come with the time-based
charts are eliminated.

118
00:07:26,450 --> 00:07:30,590
Time-based charts will always post the same
number of bars during each trading session

119
00:07:30,590 --> 00:07:34,480
regardless of volume, volatility or any other
factors.

120
00:07:34,480 --> 00:07:38,590
The only time you’ll see more range bars
printed on the chart is when we have periods

121
00:07:38,590 --> 00:07:40,260
of higher volatility.

122
00:07:40,260 --> 00:07:44,730
And even then it’s dependent on the range
bar size selected by the trader.

123
00:07:44,730 --> 00:07:50,250
Inversely, when we have low volatility, you’ll
see fewer range bars printed on the chart.

124
00:07:50,250 --> 00:07:53,740
And this is a huge improvement over classic
time frames.

125
00:07:53,740 --> 00:07:59,090
So if you ever struggled with trade management
strategies when day trading, try using range

126
00:07:59,090 --> 00:08:05,430
bars, because range bars are an effective
tool to time your entry and exit points.

127
00:08:05,430 --> 00:08:09,000
Another day trading and scalping alternative
is the tick chart.

128
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:13,260
The bars on a tick chart are created based
on a particular number of transactions.

129
00:08:13,260 --> 00:08:15,660
Again, time is irrelevant.

130
00:08:15,660 --> 00:08:20,720
For example, a 200-tick chart creates a new
bar after every 200 transactions.

131
00:08:20,720 --> 00:08:25,510
You can customize tick charts to the number
of transactions you want, for example, 5 ticks

132
00:08:25,510 --> 00:08:27,150
or 500 ticks.

133
00:08:27,150 --> 00:08:30,040
Remember, time does not play a role here.

134
00:08:30,040 --> 00:08:34,599
As tick charts are transaction based and new
bars are formed only when there are enough

135
00:08:34,599 --> 00:08:36,969
trades, the market noise is reduced.

136
00:08:36,969 --> 00:08:41,219
And you know that higher the noise, the more
difficult it becomes to make smart decisions,

137
00:08:41,219 --> 00:08:45,519
especially when day trading, when you need
to act fast.

138
00:08:45,519 --> 00:08:48,721
The main advantage of a tick chart is that
compresses low-activity trading periods.

139
00:08:48,721 --> 00:08:55,699
On a time-based chart, you may see 20-30 useless
candles, while the tick chart may offer you

140
00:08:55,699 --> 00:08:58,379
only 10-15 relevant ones.

141
00:08:58,379 --> 00:09:02,470
Tick charts can help you in placing better
stop-loss orders and take-profit levels on

142
00:09:02,470 --> 00:09:03,470
the chart.

143
00:09:03,470 --> 00:09:08,540
This is especially useful during periods of
high volatility and rapid price movements.

144
00:09:08,540 --> 00:09:13,170
And without the accumulation of small candles
like the ones on the time-based charts, tick

145
00:09:13,170 --> 00:09:16,730
charts make it easier for the trader to spot
price swings.

146
00:09:16,730 --> 00:09:22,269
I will say it once again, there is no best
time frame or a combination of time frames.

147
00:09:22,269 --> 00:09:27,149
A winning strategy can be built on any time
frame, or any combination of time frames.

148
00:09:27,149 --> 00:09:31,370
But understanding the pros and cons of each
time frame will hopefully help you decide

149
00:09:31,370 --> 00:09:33,110
which one works best for YOU.

150
00:09:33,110 --> 00:09:37,311
I’m mainly a swing trader, but when I day
trade, I tend to use a multiple time frame

151
00:09:37,311 --> 00:09:39,550
analysis using range bars.

152
00:09:39,550 --> 00:09:42,269
This works for me, but might not be your style.

153
00:09:42,269 --> 00:09:44,410
One time frame is not better than the other.

154
00:09:44,410 --> 00:09:49,121
But one may be more favorable to you because
it provides more trading opportunities, or

155
00:09:49,121 --> 00:09:50,860
has a cleaner look.

156
00:09:50,860 --> 00:09:57,100
And it’s your job to back test, analyze
and determine which one works best for you.

157
00:09:57,100 --> 00:10:00,861
